<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="49" type="supplementary description">
<paragraph pageId="6" pageNumber="49">Supplementary description.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="6" pageNumber="49">Male (Fig. 4).Elytra metallic blue, light yellowatbases and lateral margins, of which inner margins slightly wider on anterior than posterior part and distinctly wider than outer margins.Aedeagus: conjoint dorsal plate of parameres with median emargination of apical margin wide and deeper than lateral ones, protuberances between median and lateral emarginations narrowed apically and rounded at apices, about one-fourth length of ventral process of each paramere in dorsal view; ventral process of each paramere slender; median lobe presenting with a sclerotized projection in middle of dorsum, which tapered apically and bent dorsally at apex.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="6" pageNumber="49">Female. Body larger, eyes less protruding, antennae shorter and narrower than that of males, pronotum with disc slightly convex, elytra metallic blue, light yellow at bases of outer margins, all tarsal claws each with a triangular appendiculate.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="6" pageNumber="49">Body length: 7.0-9.0 mm; width: 1.5-2.3 mm.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="49" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="6" pageNumber="49">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="6" pageNumber="49">
In the original manuscript by 
<bibRefCitation author="Wittmer, W" journalOrPublisher="Entomologica Basiliensia" pageId="12" pageNumber="55" pagination="223 - 366" title="Neue Cantharidae (Col.) aus dem indo-malaiischen und palaearktischen Faunengebiet mit Mutationen. 2. Beitrag." volume="20" year="1997">Wittmer (1997)</bibRefCitation>
, the elytra of the type male was described as being partly black, which actually is metallic blue based on the examination of a series of additional specimens at our disposal. Also, it is the first time to describe the female for this species here.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="6" pageNumber="49">
Besides, the type series of this species is shown to be plural and composed of 3 species. Except the holotype, one male paratype labeled with &quot;CHINA NW, Sichuan, Min Shan, 2500-4500m, 
<geoCoordinate direction="north" orientation="latitude" precision="925" value="33.166668">33°10'N</geoCoordinate>
, 
<geoCoordinate direction="east" orientation="longitude" precision="925" value="103.833336">103°50'E</geoCoordinate>
, 14-16.vii.1990, leg. 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Jiří">Jiri</normalizedToken>
<normalizedToken originalValue="Kolibáč”">Kolibac&quot;</normalizedToken>
actually belongs to 
<taxonomicName authority="Pic, 1921" authorityName="Pic" authorityYear="1921" class="Insecta" family="Cantharidae" genus="Fissocantharis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Fissocantharis fissiformis" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fissiformis">Fissocantharis fissiformis</taxonomicName>
(
<normalizedToken originalValue="Švihla">Svihla</normalizedToken>
, 2005), the other one &quot;CHINA, Sichuan pr., Kangding distr., Hailougou Glacier Park, 21-24.vii.1992, lgt. R. Dunda&quot; is a new species described here, 
<taxonomicName authority="Pic, 1921" authorityName="Pic" authorityYear="1921" class="Insecta" family="Cantharidae" genus="Fissocantharis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Fissocantharis bicolorata" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bicolorata">Fissocantharis bicolorata</taxonomicName>
sp. n. Thus, the two paratypes of this species designated by 
<bibRefCitation author="Wittmer, W" journalOrPublisher="Entomologica Basiliensia" pageId="12" pageNumber="55" pagination="223 - 366" title="Neue Cantharidae (Col.) aus dem indo-malaiischen und palaearktischen Faunengebiet mit Mutationen. 2. Beitrag." volume="20" year="1997">Wittmer (1997)</bibRefCitation>
become invalid. In this case, this species is excluded from Sichuan province at the moment.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
